 House and Land.com 300|QLD <br/> R15]]\n|| [[2009 Queensland House and Land.com 300|QLD <br/> R16]]\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2009 L&H 500|PHI <br/> Q]]<br />{{small|13}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2009 L&H 500|PHI <br/> R17]]<br />{{small|18}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2009 Supercheap Auto Bathurst 1000|BAT <br/> R18]]<br />{{small|20}}\n| [[2009 V8 Supercar Challenge|SUR <br/> R19]]\n| [[2009 V8 Supercar Challenge|SUR <br/> R20]]\n|| [[2009 The Island 300|PHI <br/> R21]]\n|| [[2009 The Island 300|PHI <br/> R22]]\n|| [[2009 BigPond 300|PTH <br/> R23]]\n|| [[2009 BigPond 300|PTH <br/> R22]]\n|| [[Homebush Street Circuit|SYD <br/> R23]]\n|| [[Homebush Street Circuit|SYD <br/> R24]]\n! 50th\n! 180\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ben Collins (driver)}}\n* [http://www.bencollins.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collins, Ben}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bristol]]\n[[Category:English racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Indy Lights drivers]]\n[[Category:British Formula Three Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:European Le Mans Series drivers]]\n[[Category:Special Air Service soldiers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Blundell's School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:British stunt performers]]\n[[Category:FIA World Endurance Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Spa drivers]]\n[[Category:Top Gear people]]\n[[Category:ASCAR drivers]]\n[[Category:Britcar 24-hour drivers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British racing driver}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Ben Collins\n| image             = Ben Collins.jpg\n| imagesize         = 200px\n| caption           = Collins signing autographs in 2009\n| nationality       = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1975|02|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place       = [[Bristol]], [[England]]\n| prev series       = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[British Touring Car Championship|BTCC]]\n* [[V8 Supercars]]\n* [[FIA GT3 European Championship|FIA GT3]]\n* [[Le Mans Series]]\n* [[British GT Championship]]\n* [[VSR V8 Trophy|ASCAR]]\n* [[FIA Sportscar Championship|FIA Sportscars]]\n* [[French Formula Three Championship|French Formula Three]]\n* [[Firestone Indy Lights|Indy Lights]]\n* [[FIA Sportscar Championship|Int'l Sports Racing]]\n* [[FIA GT Championship]]\n* [[British Formula 3 Championship|British Formula 3]]\n* Formula Vauxhall Junior\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| prev series years = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[2010 British Touring Car Championship season|2010]]\n* [[2009 V8 Supercar Championship Series|2009]]\n* 2006\u201307\n* [[2006 Le Mans Series season|2006]], [[2010 Le Mans Series season|2010]]\u2013[[2011 Le Mans Series season|11]]\n* 2005\n* 2003\n* 2001\n* 2000\n* [[1999 Indy Lights season|1999]]\n* [[1998 International Sports Racing Series season|1998]]\n* [[1997 FIA GT Championship season|1997]]\n* 1996\u201398, 2000\u201301\n* 1995\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| titles            = [[VSR V8 Trophy|ASCAR]]\n| title years       = 2003\n| module =\n  {{Infobox Le Mans driver\n  |child=yes\n  |Years = {{24hLM|2001}}, {{24hLM|2002}}, {{24hLM|2011}}, {{24hLM|2014}}\n  |Team(s) = [[Ascari Cars|Team Ascari]], [[RML Group|RML]]\n  |Best Finish = 12th\n  |Class Wins = 0\n  }}\n}}\n'''Ben Lievesley Collins''' (born 13 February 1975)<ref>Speedsport Magazine, [http://www.speedsport-magazine.com/race-driver-database/biography/Ben-Collins-,163.html Race Driver Database: Ben Collins]. Retrieved 15 March 2008.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=X9s2ev6o8wwMME3O8CM%2BBQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=13 December 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> is a [[racing]] driver from [[Bristol]], England. He has competed in motor racing since 1994 in many categories, from [[Formula Three]] and [[Indy Lights]] to sportscars, GT racing and stock cars.\n\nCollins was placed second in the Marlboro Masters Formula 3 championship event in 2000. He set the pace at the 2001 [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans 24 hours race]] in his first season for approximately four hours during the rain at night. After winning the European Stock Car Championship in 2003 [[Stock Car Speed Association|ASCAR]] [[stock car racing]] he was signed by [[PDM Racing]] to do selected rounds of the 2004 [[Indy Racing League]], but the car never appeared. In 2005, he competed in the British GT Championship in a [[Porsche 911|Porsche 996 GT3]], winning races on the way before moving up to the FIA GT Series with Ascari where he led races and scored several pole positions.\n\nIn addition to racing, Collins' company '''Collins Autosport Limited''' provides precision and stunt driving services, particularly for [[BBC Television]], including ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV Series)|Top Gear]]''<ref name=\"telegraph-outing\"/><ref name=\"times-open-secret\"/> and ''Top Gear Live'', as well as for the film industry, such as driving [[James Bond]]'s car in ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'' and ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'', and [[Eve Moneypenny]]'s car in ''[[Skyfall]]''.\n\nIn August 2010, the ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' alleged that Collins may be one of the identities of [[The Stig]]\u2014an otherwise unidentified presenter on the ''Top Gear'' show\u2014on the basis of financial filing made by the Collins Autosport company.{{cn|date=February 2020}} On 1 September 2010 the BBC was refused a court injunction preventing Collins from publishing an autobiography revealing himself to be The Stig.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hewage|first=Tim|title=Top Gear's The Stig Is Finally Unmasked|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Top-Gears-Stig-Is-Free-To-Publish-Autobiography-After-BBC-Lose-Bid-To-Get-Injunction/Article/201009115710574?lpos=UK_News_First_UK_News_Article_Teaser_Region_2&lid=ARTICLE_15710574_Top_Gears_Stig_Is_Free_To_Publish_Autobiography_After_BBC_Lose_Bid_To_Get_Injunction|accessdate=1 September 2010|publisher=[[Sky News]]|date=1 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100904071903/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/Top-Gears-Stig-Is-Free-To-Publish-Autobiography-After-BBC-Lose-Bid-To-Get-Injunction/Article/201009115710574?lpos=UK_News_First_UK_News_Article_Teaser_Region_2&lid=ARTICLE_15710574_Top_Gears_Stig_Is_Free_To_Publish_Autobiography_After_BBC_Lose_Bid_To_Get_Injunction|archivedate=4 September 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 1 October 2010, it was announced that Collins would join ''[[Fifth Gear]]'' as a presenter.<ref name=\"Sweney-10-01\">{{cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark |title='The Stig' joins Channel 5's Fifth Gear|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/oct/01/the-stig-top-gear-channel-5|accessdate=1 October 2010|newspaper=The Guardian|date=10 January 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101001133637/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2010/oct/01/the-stig-top-gear-channel-5| archivedate= 1 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 2012 Collins joined as co-presenter of Polish [[TVN (Poland)|TVN]]'s ''[[Automaniak]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvn.pl/showbiz/nowy-sezon-automaniaka-z-legendarnym-benem-collinsem,38447,341,0,0.html |title=Nowy sezon \"Automaniaka\" z legendarnym Benem Collinsem! |publisher=Tvn.pl |date=2013-11-11 |accessdate=2015-01-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012032552/http://www.tvn.pl/showbiz/nowy-sezon-automaniaka-z-legendarnym-benem-collinsem,38447,341,0,0.html |archive-date=12 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In February 2014, he was added to the 'Drivers Club' of the newly formed [[FIA Formula E Championship|Formula E]] series, but did not compete in the inaugural 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiaformulae.com/news/formula-e-completes-drivers-club |title=Alguersuari, Minassian & Klien add names to Formula E Drivers\u2019 Club|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508121951/http://www.fiaformulae.com/news/formula-e-completes-drivers-club|archivedate=8 May 2014|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCollins was born in Bristol, but spent the first ten years of his life in [[California]] in the USA, where his father worked for a distribution company. Collins was educated at [[Blundell's School]] and after studying law at the [[University of Exeter]], he spent around four years serving in the [[British Army]], serving some of his time as a [[Special Forces]] driving instructor.<ref name=\"ogrady\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/so-hes-really-the-stig-big-deal-2059348.html|title=So he's really the Stig? Big deal|first=Sean|last=O'Grady|work=Independent|date=23 August 2010|accessdate=23 August 2010 | location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100824065908/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/so-hes-really-the-stig-big-deal-2059348.html| archivedate= 24 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/13/business/media/13cache.html|title=BBC and News Corp. Sharpen Attacks in Top Gear Scuffle|work=New York Times|first=Eric|last=Pfanner|date=12 September 2010|accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref>  His racing career started in 1994.<ref name=\"ogrady\"/>  He worked for Hornby as brand manager of the ''[[Scalextric]]'' model [[slot car]] division.<ref name=\"ogrady\"/><ref name=\"city-speakers\"/>  {{As of|2010}} Collins continued to live in Bristol.<ref name=\"bloxham\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/news/7958512/Stig-mystery-financial-documents-suggest-identity-of-Top-Gear-driver.html|title=Stig mystery: financial documents suggest identity of Top Gear driver|first=Andy|last=Bloxham|work=Telegraph|date=22 August 2010|accessdate=23 August 2010 | location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100823233438/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/news/7958512/Stig-mystery-financial-documents-suggest-identity-of-Top-Gear-driver.html| archivedate= 23 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Racing==\n[[File:BenCollins.jpg|left|thumb|Ben Collins driving the No.84 car in the 2003 European [[Stock Car Speed Association|SCSA]] championship]]\nCollins has competed in motorsport since 1994.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsautosport.com/bencollins_biog.php|title=Collins Autosport: Racing History|work=collinsautosport.com|publisher=Collins Autosport|accessdate=24 August 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825043851/http://www.collinsautosport.com/bencollins_biog.php|archivedate=25 August 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1995 he competed in Formula Vauxhall Junior, finishing third overall with two wins and eight podiums. He also competed in the Formula Opel Winter Series, placing second overall driving for [[Sir Jackie Stewart]] who commented in ''Autosport Magazine'', \"When you see the likes of Ben Collins in Formula One, remember you saw them here first\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Collins|url=http://www.lawagency.co.uk/speaker/ben-collins|publisher=Lucas Alexander Whitley|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> The following season he competed briefly in Formula Vauxhall for Martin Donnelly, scoring a 2nd place finish in the opening round at Donington Park - Martin remarked that \"Ben is an aggressive driver with phenomenal natural speed.\" \n\nCollins moved onto the [[British Formula 3 Championship]] in [[1996 British Formula 3 season|1996]]. In [[1997 British Formula 3 season|1997]], he finished eighth in the standings driving for [[Fortec Motorsport]], and also finished eighth in the [[Macau Grand Prix]].<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.driverdb.com/drivers/367/career/|title=Ben Collins career statistics|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> After another year in Formula Three in [[1998 British Formula 3 season|1998]], Collins raced in the American [[Indy Lights]] series in 1999, finishing thirteen in the standings.<ref name=\"stats\"/> For 2000, he returned to British F3 to drive for [[Carlin Motorsport]], once again finishing eighth. He also finished second in the [[2000 Masters of Formula 3]] race at [[Circuit Park Zandvoort|Zandvoort]].\nCollins has been a [[test driver]] for racing manufacturer [[Ascari Cars|Ascari]] during [[Ascari A10]] development,<ref>Surface Transforms Plc, [http://www.systemst.com/case-studies/Ascari/A10/ Case Study: Ascari A10] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114022636/http://www.systemst.com/case-studies/Ascari/A10/ |date=14 January 2009 }}. Retrieved 12 June 2008.</ref> and undertaken testing of [[Formula One]] cars.<ref name=\"haroon\"/>\n\nIn 2001, Collins raced in the [[FIA Sportscar Championship]] for [[Ascari Cars|Team Ascari]], with [[Werner Lupberger]], the pair winning at [[Donington Park]] and finishing joint sixth in the standings. The team also raced at the [[2001 24 Hours of Le Mans]]. Collins also finished sixth at the [[2002 12 Hours of Sebring]] for Ascari.\n\nIn 2003, Collins raced in the [[VSR V8 Trophy|ASCAR]] European Oval racing series with [[RML Group|RML]], winning six races on his way to being crowned champion. He continued racing in the series in 2004.\n\nCollins returned to sportscars in 2005 to race in the [[British GT Championship]] and [[FIA GT Championship]] with [[Embassy Racing]], placing 3rd in the series. \n\nIn 2006 he rejoined Ascari, racing in the [[FIA GT3 European Championship]].\n\nIn 2007 Collins tested a [[NASCAR Cup Series]] car at [[USA International Speedway|Lakeland Speedway]] with the [[Red Bull Racing Team]].\n\nIn 2009 Collins was named as an endurance driver for Australian [[V8 Supercars]] team, [[Kelly Racing|Kelly Racing/Jack Daniel's Racing]], partnering with [[Nathan Pretty]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Collins joins Jack Daniel's Racing|url=http://www.motorsport.com/v8supercars/news/ben-collins-joins-jack-daniel-s-racing/|publisher=Motorsport|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2010 Le Mans Series season]], he was racing for [[RML Group|RML AD Group]]. His first race for the team was the [[2010 1000 km of Algarve]], finishing fourth overall and winning the LMP2 class.<ref>{{cite web|title=1000km Algarve Race results|url=http://www.automobilsport.com/race-categories--24,83378,1000km-Algarve-Race-results,news.htm|publisher=AutoMobilSport|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref> He remained with the team for the next round, the [[2010 1000 km of Hungaroring]], where they finished fourth in both class and overall.\n\nCollins competed in the final meeting of the 2010 Dunlop MSA [[British Touring Car Championship]], driving a BMW for the [[Motorbase Performance]] team. He finished his first race in 14th and bettered that with a 12th in his second. However he retired in the third and he never returned the following season.\n\n==Collins Autosport==\nCollins is a regular writer for ''Autosport Magazine'' testing the latest racing cars, has written for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', fronted [[Sky Sports|Sky Sports']] televised NASCAR coverage, along with appearances on the British car-focused television programmes ''[[Top Gear (current format)|Top Gear]]'' ([[BBC Two]]), ''[[Pulling Power]]'' ([[ITV1]]) and ''[[driven (TV series)|driven]]'' ([[Channel 4]]).<ref name=\"city-speakers\"/>\n\nHe worked as a precision-driver in the film ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]'' where he doubled for the actor [[Nicolas Cage]] and drove in some of the high-speed sequences in London.<ref name=\"cg-lock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cg-lock.co.uk/downloads/pdf/as08-stunts.pdf|format=PDF|title=Blockbuster Movie Uses the CG-Lock|date=10 January 2007|publisher=CG-Lock}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wildaboutmovies.com/movies/National-Treasure-2-Movie.php|title=\"National Treasure 2\" AKA \"National Treasure: Book Of Secrets\"|publisher=Wild about Movies|quote=a contraption actually mounted on the roof of the Mercedes-Benz C-Class vehicle which allowed famed British driver Ben Collins the ability to do the actual driving, while Turteltaub and cinematographer John Schwartzman shot Nicolas Cage, Diane Kruger and Justin Bartha inside of the vehicle|accessdate=24 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090602084744/http://www.wildaboutmovies.com/movies/National-Treasure-2-Movie.php| archivedate= 2 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> As a precision-driver in the 2008-film ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'', Collins drove James Bond's [[Aston Martin DBS]] as a [[stunt double]] for [[Daniel Craig]] in the lead role.<ref name=\"haroon\"/><ref name=\"telegraph-outing\"/><ref name=\"ogrady\"/><ref name=\"city-speakers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityspeakersinternational.co.uk/speakers/speaker_ben_collins.php|title=Ben Collins \u2013 Motivational Speaker|accessdate=19 January 2009|publisher=City Speakers International|quote=He will limber up for this year's racing season by doubling as James Bond...|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123062339/http://cityspeakersinternational.co.uk/speakers/speaker_ben_collins.php|archivedate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has also worked as a stunt driver on [[Skyfall]] and [[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]].\n\nHe also holds a World Record for the maximum distance of driving a car on two wheels (a manoeuvre called \"[[Ski (driving stunt)|skiing]]\").<ref name=\"city-speakers\"/>\n\nCollins presented television programme ''[[Xtreme Teen Drivers]]'',<ref name=\"city-speakers\"/> shown on [[BBC Three]] on 15 December 2007; as an advanced driving instructor within the programme, he was trying to teach a young [[boy racer (sub-culture)|boy racer]] to drive more safely.\n\nCollins' company Ben Collins Auto-sport has provided its logistics and third-party [[liability insurance]] for prize-winner [[track day]] events promoted by [[Top Gear (magazine)|''Top Gear'' magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://traitors.topgear.com/terms/|work=Nissan Motor GB Ltd and BBC Magazines Limited Joint Promotion|title=Terms and Conditions|quote=21. Ben Collins Auto-sport has third party and public liability insurance cover for all of its operation|publisher=BBC Magazines Ltd|accessdate=14 April 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405223559/http://traitors.topgear.com/terms/|archivedate=5 April 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===''Top Gear''===\nCollins has appeared on the popular BBC television programme ''[[Top Gear (current format)|Top Gear]]'' as himself,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11058504|title=HarperCollins in Top Gear Stig legal wrangle|work=BBC News |date=23 August 2010|accessdate=23 August 2010|quote=appeared numerous times on the programme and he often supplied other drivers for both the programme and Top Gear Live.| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100823194529/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11058504| archivedate= 23 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> with his company providing drivers and driving services since December 2003.<ref name=\"haroon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/aug/22/top-gear-bbc-stig-memoirs|title=Top Gear driver unmasked as Sunday Times lifts helmet on Stig's identity|first=Haroon|last=Siddique|work=The Guardian|date=22 August 2010|accessdate=23 August 2010|quote=In December 2003, .. based partly on \"driving services provided for the BBC, mainly in the Top Gear programme\". | location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100824221304/http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2010/aug/22/top-gear-bbc-stig-memoirs| archivedate= 24 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In Series&nbsp;2 Episode&nbsp;10, Collins appeared as one member of ''BBC Top Gear''-team in the 24-hour [[Citro\u00ebn 2CV]] racing event. The team finished thirteenth, out of thirty four cars, 24 laps behind the leaders, with Collins setting fastest lap.\n\nIn 2004, Collins made an appearance during the fourth series of ''Top Gear'', alongside [[parachutist]] Tim Carter.<ref name=\"parachute\">Crash.net, [http://www.crash.net/motorsport/f1/news/96604-0/ Reigning champion stars on BBC Top Gear] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315003122/http://www.crash.net/motorsport/f1/news/96604-0/ |date=15 March 2008 }}, 27 July 2004.</ref> The stunt involved Carter and an [[camera operator|aerial cameraman]] jumping out of a [[Cessna]] light aircraft then landing in the [[convertible (car)|open-topped]] [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] car being driven at a speed by Collins.<ref name=\"unmasked-at-last\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Stig-unmasked/article-2557405-detail/article.html|title=Has The Stig been unmasked at last?|work=Evening Post|location=Bristol|date=23 August 2010|accessdate=24 August 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826072922/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Stig-unmasked/article-2557405-detail/article.html|archivedate=26 August 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The open-top car was introduced as belonging to Collins and had earlier been used, driven by [[The Stig]], during a wig test in Series&nbsp;3 Episode&nbsp;5.\n\nIn 2004, the driver featured during series five, driving a [[Lancer Evo#Evolution VII|Lancer Evo VII]] and then a [[Bowler Wildcat]] vehicle in a [[rally racing|rally race]] against [[mountain boarding]] world champion Tom Kirkman<ref name=\"unmasked-at-last\"/><ref name=\"mountainboard\">{{cite web |work=www.bbc.co.uk| title=Calstock's own World champion | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cornwall/extremesports/stories/apr_2005/tom_kirkham_mountainboarding.shtml | accessdate=26 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"skateboard2\">{{cite web |work=www.youtube.com| title=Top Gear: Skater | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-9AKp35gDco | accessdate=7 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of series six, Collins appeared with other [[British Touring Car Championship]] racing and stunt drivers for a [[Five-a-side football]] game using a fleet of [[Toyota Aygo]] cars.<ref name=\"unmasked-at-last\"/> Collins played in a [[team]] [[Captain (association football)|captained]] by ''Top Gear'' presenter [[Richard Hammond]]. The other drivers were [[Paul Swift (Driver)|Paul Swift]], [[Tim Harvey]] and [[Tom Chilton]] (blue team); playing against [[James May]], [[Russ Swift]], [[Matt Neal]], [[Dan Eaves]] and [[Rob Huff]] (red team).\n\nCollins could be seen driving the [[Honda Civic Type-R]] against [[Jeremy Clarkson]] in Episode 6 of Series 10.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Stig|url=http://samples.sainsburysebooks.co.uk/9781488507571_sample_274554.pdf|publisher=Sainsburys|accessdate=29 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305034344/http://samples.sainsburysebooks.co.uk/9781488507571_sample_274554.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe sixth episode of series seventeen of ''Top Gear'' featured a team of amputee soldiers training driving a [[Bowler Wildcat]] and being trained by Collins to take part in the [[Dakar Rally]].<ref name=\"hogan\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8668472/Top-Gear-episode-6-review.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Top Gear, episode 6, review|date=31 July 2011|accessdate=1 August 2011|first=Michael|last=Hogan}}</ref>\n\nCollins also appeared in the Top Gear Special, '50 Years of Bond Cars', on the set of [[Skyfall]]. Collins, who worked as a stunt driver on the film was interviewed by [[Richard Hammond]].\n\nOn a separate occasion, following an accident involving [[Richard Hammond]] in September 2006, the [[Health & Safety Executive]] report into the event recorded that Collins had \"worked closely with ''Top Gear'' as a high-performance driver and consultant\" and had prepared a briefing for Richard Hammond preceding the event.<ref name=\"hse\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/foi/releases/richardhammond.htm|title=Investigation into the accident of Richard Hammond|website=www.hse.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\n====The Stig====\n[[File:The Stig British International Motor Show.jpg|right|thumb|The Stig]]\nOn 19 January 2009, British newspaper ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' ran a story claiming that they had \"outed\" Collins as being one of the people behind the white-suit incarnation of [[The Stig]], at the same time noting that \"Collins, from Bristol, has always denied being the Stig\".<ref name=\"telegraph-outing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/4286448/Who-is-the-Stig-The-answer.html|title=Who is the Stig? The answer|date=19 January 2009|quote=Top Gear test driver the Stig has been unmasked as professional stuntman and Le Mans racer Ben Collins.|accessdate=19 January 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090121211442/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/4286448/Who-is-the-Stig-The-answer.html| archivedate= 21 January 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Times]]'', in a follow-up article, stated that the \"identity of the white-suited Stig ... has been an [[open secret]] within the motoring world for some years, with newspapers refraining from publishing his name, to uphold the spirit of the programme\" which concluded that \"a newspaper broke with the convention to out Mr Collins, 33,<!--literal quote from article DO NOT CHANGE from '33'--> after following up a story in a Bristol newspaper\".<ref name=\"times-open-secret\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/driving/article5548705.ece|title=Identity of Top Gear's The Stig revealed as Ben Collins|first=Patrick|last=Foster|date=19 January 2009|accessdate=19 January 2009|work=The Times |location=UK }}</ref>\nSimilar allegations were repeated by ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' during August 2010.\n\nTwo Bristol-based local newspapers had published articles a week before ''The Times'' in January 2009, on the basis of information leaked from a local art gallery. Collins had previously commissioned a [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]]-based business in September 2008, to produce a limited-edition run of poster prints.<ref name=\"western-daily\"/> Collins had initially portrayed himself as a BBC marketing executive<ref name=\"western-daily\"/> and only confirmed a more detailed connection to the ''Top Gear'' show after the signing of confidentiality agreements by the business owners.<ref name=\"western-daily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Gear-s-Stig-reveals-identity-Bristol-gallery-owners/article-589665-detail/article.html|title=Top Gear's The Stig reveals identity to Bristol gallery owners|date=6 January 2009|accessdate=19 January 2009|work=[[Western Daily Press]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123030059/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Gear-s-Stig-reveals-identity-Bristol-gallery-owners/article-589665-detail/article.html|archivedate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"bristol-news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Gear-s-Stig-revealed-Bristol-firm/article-589703-detail/article.html|title=Top Gear's The Stig revealed to Bristol firm|date=6 January 2009|accessdate=19 January 2009|work=Bristol News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123030054/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Gear-s-Stig-revealed-Bristol-firm/article-589703-detail/article.html|archivedate=23 January 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe signed poster image showed a [[Salt pan (geology)|salt flat]] scene, with The Stig positioned standing on it.<ref name=\"unmasked-at-last\"/><ref name=\"bristol-news\"/>\n\nHowever, at the time ''Top Gear'' presenter [[James May]] claimed that the Stig's identity had not been outed.  There had been speculation that there may have been more than one person who plays the Stig.<ref name=\"daily-telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/4321313/The-Stigs-true-identity-is-still-a-mystery-claims-Top-Gears-James-May.html|title=The Stig's true identity is still a mystery, claims Top Gear's James May|date=23 January 2009|accessdate=24 January 2009|work=Daily Telegraph | location=London | first=Nick | last=Allen| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090131224929/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/4321313/The-Stigs-true-identity-is-still-a-mystery-claims-Top-Gears-James-May.html| archivedate= 31 January 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n====Autobiography publication====\n{{main|BBC v HarperCollins Publishers Ltd}}\nDuring August to September 2010 the BBC started legal proceedings against Harper Collins, with the BBC attempting to obtain a [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] [[injunction]] to prevent the publishing of a book entitled ''The Man in The White Suit'', apparently authored by Collins. The injunction was quashed by the High Court, allowing the possibility of the book being published on its intended release date of 16 September 2010 in the United Kingdom and 1 October 2010 in Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/top-gear-creators-original-stig-living-in-sydney/story-e6frg6nf-1225919884394|title=Top Gear creator's original Stig living in Sydney|work=The Australian|date=13 September 2010|accessdate=12 September 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914040100/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/top-gear-creators-original-stig-living-in-sydney/story-e6frg6nf-1225919884394| archivedate= 14 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn an exclusive interview with ''WitneyTV'' recorded on 3 September 2010 and broadcast on 7 September 2010, ''Top Gear''-presenter Jeremy Clarkson confirmed that Collins had worked as The Stig, and that Collins was \"history as far as we're concerned, he's sacked\".<ref>{{cite episode|type=Video interview |url=http://www.witneytv.co.uk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703122148/http://www.witneytv.co.uk/ |archivedate= 3 July 2010 |airdate=2010-09-07 |title=Jeremy Clarkson interview |series=[[Witney#Media|WitneyTV]] |seriesno=01 |number=17 |minutes=26:56\u201329:10 |quote=he's history as far as we're concerned, he's sacked |url-status=dead }}</ref>  On 7/8 September 2010, ''The Guardian'', ''The Sun'' and other papers re-reported Clarkson's assertions in the interview that Collins had been fired from his role on the television show.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/07/jeremy-clarkson-stig-sacked|title=Jeremy Clarkson: the Stig is 'sacked'|work=The Guardian|first=Tara|last=Conlan|date=7 September 2010|accessdate=11 September 2010 | location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100910085956/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2010/sep/07/jeremy-clarkson-stig-sacked| archivedate= 10 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn the fifteenth series Christmas special, ''Top Gear'' presenters referred to the Stig as \"The Splitter\" and publicly ridiculed the Stig, using the picture of the Stig for drive-by shooting targets.\n\nDuring Collins' appearance with the military amputees broadcast in July 2011, Collins was introduced and acknowledged by ''Top Gear''-presenter Richard Hammond as \"ex-Stig ... Ben Collins\".<ref name=\"hogan\"/> Though Hammond still referred to Collins as a \"romantic novelist\", he said that \"to be honest, [he was] quite glad to see 'the old Splitter' back, and [he does] know how much giving these guys a hand means to him. So this is all right.\"\n\nIn his appearance in the ''Top Gear'' Special, '50 Years of Bond Cars', Collins was wearing a T-shirt on which was printed the words, \"I AM THE STIG.\" [[Richard Hammond]], (who interviewed Collins) reacted, saying to him, \"Nice T-shirt by the way.\" Collins admitted that he needs to \"update that a bit\", pointing to the word \"AM\", to which Hammond exclaimed, \"Was.\" After hearing about some of what Collins had been doing for the film, Hammond remarked, \"You should write a book.\"\n\n===''Fifth Gear''===\nCollins joined the presenting staff of [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]'s ''[[Fifth Gear]]'' in Series 18, participating in racing challenges on several occasions. He did not return to the cast for Series 19.\n\n===Other work===\n\nFollowing his departure from ''Top Gear'', Collins has subsequently appeared on the \"Top Gear Live\" touring show. He appeared onstage in a show in Poland and also served as a racing driver for at least one pre-recorded clip.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hammond|first1=Richard|title=Hammond, Clarkson and May found a new racing driver.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=3&v=MYJZG5Og2yg|website=YouTube|publisher=Richard Hammond|accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref> Introducing him, Clarkson joked Collins' was \"living rough\", in a racing track paddock, as Collins was shown to be sleeping on cardboard with a shopping trolley with books and Daniel Craig face cuttouts for his possessions. Collins' role was identical to his previous one as the Stig, except wearing an open face helmet and he was referred to as \"The Ben Collins\" by Clarkson. He has written a second book, ''How To Drive: The Ultimate Guide, from the Man Who Was The Stig,'' published in 2014.\n\nCollins served as a consultant during the development of [[Project CARS]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/cars/ex-stig-ben-collins-talks-development-of-project-cars/|title=How The Stig traded in his white helmet for an Oculus Rift and Project Cars|date=26 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and [[Project CARS 2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://me.askmen.com/cars/1103510/article/ben-collins-on-why-project-cars-2-is-the-best-racing-sim-yet|title=Ben Collins On Why Project Cars 2 Is The Best Racing Sim Yet|date=16 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Collins started a career as a stunt driver in the Nicolas Cage movie \"National Treasure 2.\" This followed by multiple films for the James Bond franchise <ref>https://www.irishnews.com/magazine/entertainment/2019/06/20/news/james-bond-stunt-driver-could-not-bare-to-watch-aston-martin-destroyed-1645955/</ref> and other blockbusters including \"Dark Knight Rises\", \"Han Solo: A Star Wars Story\", \"Jack Ryan\", and \"Mission Impossible.\" He had a dual role as a stunt driver and actor in [[Ford_v_Ferrari|\"Ford v Ferrari / Le Mans '66\"]] in the role of [[Denny Hulme]] <ref>https://www.motorious.com/articles/news/370554/ford-v-ferrari-excitement-building</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===24 Hours of Le Mans results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! Laps\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>Pos.|Class position}}\n|-\n! [[2001 24 Hours of Le Mans|2001]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ascari Cars|Team Ascari]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[Werner Lupberger]]<br>{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Harri Toivonen]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Ascari A410]]-[[Judd (engine)|Judd]]\n| LMP900\n| 134\n| DNF\n| DNF\n|-\n! [[2002 24 Hours of Le Mans|2002]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ascari Cars|Team Ascari]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|ZAF}} [[Werner Lupberger]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[T. J. Bell]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Ascari A410|Ascari KZR-1]]-[[Judd (engine)|Judd]]\n| LMP1\n| 17\n| DNF\n| DNF\n|-\n! [[2011 24 Hours of Le Mans|2011]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[RML Group|RML]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Mike Newton (racing driver)|Mike Newton]]<br>{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Thomas Erdos]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[HPD ARX-01d]]\n| LMP2\n| 314\n| 12th\n| 4th\n|-\n! [[2014 24 Hours of Le Mans|2014]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Krohn Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tracy Krohn]]<br>{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Niclas J\u00f6nsson]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Ferrari 458 Italia GT2]]\n| GTE<br>Am\n| 325\n| 30th\n| 10th\n|}\n\n===24 Hours of Silverstone result